                            <comment id="23383" author="vishal.puri" created="Mon, 23 Apr 2007 13:58:00 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;There is a point here &quot;The username should be a required parameter. If the username parameter is not supplied, then the request is malformed and should be rejected&quot;  but the following code handles this issue very well &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;        // load the user by name&lt;br/&gt;
        UserDetails targetUser = this.userDetailsService.loadUserByUsername(username);&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;        // user not found&lt;br/&gt;
        if (targetUser == null) {&lt;br/&gt;
            throw new UsernameNotFoundException(messages.getMessage(&quot;SwitchUserProcessingFilter.usernameNotFound&quot;,&lt;br/&gt;
                    new Object[] &lt;/p&gt;
{username}
&lt;p&gt;, &quot;Username &lt;/p&gt;
{0}
&lt;p&gt; not found&quot;));&lt;br/&gt;
        }&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If HttpServletRequest contained an empty or null username the targetUser will be null and hence UsernameNotFoundException will be thrown. I have added a junit test to prove adding a null username in HttpServletRequest does indeed throw UsernameNotFoundException.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="23389" author="vishal.puri" created="Mon, 23 Apr 2007 17:44:23 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I have incorporated a JUnit test  which confirms the propagation of the  expected exception.  Hence, this issue is closed.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
